# 🏛️ Section 5: Loop Controls & Optimization

---

### 5.1 Loops Overview
* **`for` Loop:** Best when you know the number of iterations in advance.
* **`while` Loop:** Best when the loop runs based on a condition rather than a count.
* **`do-while` Loop:** Similar to the while loop, but guarantees the block runs **at least once** before checking the condition.

---

### 5.2 Infinite Loops & Browser Freezes
An infinite loop occurs when the loop condition never becomes false (e.g. omitting the loop counter increment step). Because JavaScript is single-threaded, an infinite loop blocks the Call Stack, preventing user clicks, layout rendering, and event handlers. This freezes the browser tab.

#### Infinite Loop Example (Do Not Run):
```javascript
// This loop will run forever because i never changes
let i = 1;
while (i < 5) {
    console.log("Infinite Loop");
    // Missing i++
}
```

---

### 5.3 Loop Optimization Comparison
For peak performance:
* Minimize work inside the loop body.
* Cache the array length rather than reading it on every iteration:
```javascript
let arr = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5];
// Optimized: length read once, not checked on every loop iteration
for (let i = 0, len = arr.length; i < len; i++) {
    console.log(arr[i]);
}
```

---

# 🏛️ Section 6: Break and Continue Execution Modifiers

---

### 6.1 `break` Statement
Instantly exits the loop body. Control flow jumps to the statement immediately following the loop.

---

### 6.2 `continue` Statement
Skips the remaining code inside the loop block for the current iteration and jumps directly to the next condition check/iteration step.

---

### Code Example:
```html
<script>
    console.log("Break Demo:");
    for (let i = 1; i <= 5; i++) {
        if (i === 4) break; // Stops loop completely
        console.log(i); // Prints 1, 2, 3
    }

    console.log("Continue Demo:");
    for (let i = 1; i <= 5; i++) {
        if (i === 3) continue; // Skips printing 3
        console.log(i); // Prints 1, 2, 4, 5
    }
</script>
```

