# 🏛️ Section 9: Event Handler & Event Propagation

---

### 9.1 Mouse Events
* `onclick`: Single click.
* `ondblclick`: Double click.
* `onmouseover` / `onmouseout`: Triggers when mouse cursor enters or leaves the element's boundary.

---

### 9.2 Keyboard Events
* `onkeyup`: Triggered when a pressed key is released.
* `onkeypress`: Triggered when a character key is pressed down (deprecated in modern standards).

---

### 9.3 Focus Events
* `onfocus`: Triggered when an element gains focus (e.g. clicking into a text box).
* `onblur`: Triggered when an element loses focus.

---

### 9.4 Form/Window Events
* `onload`: Triggers after the page resource dependencies (images, scripts, CSS) have finished loading.
* `onchange`: Triggers when an element's value changes (e.g. select element choice).
* `onsubmit`: Triggers before a form submits.
* `onreset`: Triggers when form fields are reset.

---

### 9.5 Event Propagation (Bubbling vs Capturing)
When an event happens on an element inside another element, browsers run two phases:
1. **Capturing Phase:** The event starts at the root `window` and travels down the DOM tree to the target element.
2. **Bubbling Phase (Default):** The event starts at the target element and travels up the DOM tree to the root `window`.

```
  Capturing Phase (Down)         Bubbling Phase (Up)
      window                         window  ^
        |                              |     |
      <body>                           <body>|
        |                              |     |
      <div> (Target) ---------> Element Target
```

---

### 9.6 Prevent Default Behavior
Use `event.preventDefault()` to stop the browser's default behavior for an event (such as preventing a submit button from reloading the page).

#### Example Code:
```html
<a href="https://google.com" id="myLink">Google</a>
<script>
    document.getElementById("myLink").addEventListener("click", function(event) {
        event.preventDefault(); // Prevents browser from navigating to link
        console.log("Navigation blocked!");
    });
</script>
```

